s_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhile German unification promised a new historical beginning, it also stirred discussions about contemporary Germany’s Nazi past and ideas of citizenship and belonging in a changing Europe. Minority Discourses in Germany Since 1990 explores the intersections and divergences between Black German, Turkish German, and German Jewish experiences, with reflections on the evolving academic paradigms with which these are studied. Informed by comparative approaches, the volume investigates social and aesthetic interventions into contemporary German public and political discourse on memory, racism, citizenship, immigration, and history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aGerman literaturexMinority authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aGerman literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aGerman literaturey21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aMinorities in literature. 0aMinorities in mass media. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh  aHistory: 20th Century to Present, Refugee and Migration Studies.1 aAdelson, Leslie A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlock, Nick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaspari, Maya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDickinson, Kristin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDischereit, Esther, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGezen, Ela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGezen, Ela, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGueneli, Berna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKallin, Britta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLandry, Olivia, econ